definitions: relating to or used for determining position and planning routes
examples: The ship's navigational equipment failed during the storm
Modern cars include advanced navigational systems with GPS

definitions: uncivilized, brutish, or showing lack of intelligence or refinement
relating to extinct human species that lived in Europe and Asia
examples: His neanderthal approach to problem-solving involved only brute force
Their neanderthal attitudes toward women belong in the past
Scientists discovered neanderthal fossils in the cave system
The museum displayed neanderthal tools and weapons from prehistoric times

definitions: arranged in an orderly way with everything in place
done with skill, efficiency, or in a clever way
undiluted, especially referring to alcoholic drinks served without mixing
examples: She kept her desk neat with papers filed properly
The neat rows of vegetables made the garden look organized
That was a neat trick with the playing cards
The programmer found a neat solution to the complex problem
He ordered his whiskey neat at the bar
She prefers her vodka neat rather than mixed

definitions: unclear, vague, or ill-defined in form or character
having the form of a cloud or haze
examples: Their nebulous plans lacked specific details or deadlines
The contract contained nebulous language open to interpretation
The nebulous shapes in the fog made navigation difficult
Astronomers studied the nebulous formations in deep space

definitions: having a neck of specified type or length
examples: The long-necked giraffe reached the highest tree branches
She wore a high-necked sweater to stay warm

definitions: born with the name that follows, used for maiden names
examples: Mrs. Johnson, nee Smith, attended her high school reunion
The author Sarah Williams, nee Davis, published her memoir

definitions: required as useful, just, or proper for a purpose
examples: The needed repairs to the roof couldn't wait longer
She gathered all the needed documents for her visa application

definitions: not needed or required; unnecessary and could be avoided
examples: The accident caused needless suffering that proper planning would prevent
Their needless complaints about minor issues wasted everyone's time

definitions: lacking basic necessities of life such as food or money
requiring excessive emotional support or attention from others
examples: The charity provides meals for needy families in the community
Government programs assist needy students with school supplies
Her needy behavior drove friends away with constant demands
The needy child required constant reassurance from teachers

definitions: extremely wicked or villainous, typically involving criminal activities
examples: The villain's nefarious plot threatened the entire city's safety
Police uncovered their nefarious scheme to defraud elderly investors

definitions: not receiving proper attention or care; abandoned or ignored
examples: The neglected garden became overgrown with weeds and vines
Neglected children often struggle with trust issues later in life

definitions: not giving proper care or attention to someone or something
examples: The neglectful parent rarely attended their child's school events
Being neglectful of safety procedures caused the workplace accident

definitions: failing to take proper care in doing something, especially legally required
examples: The negligent driver caused the accident by texting while driving
The company was negligent in maintaining proper safety standards

definitions: so small or unimportant as to be not worth considering
examples: The difference in price was negligible between the two options
Side effects from the medication proved negligible for most patients

definitions: open to discussion or modification through mutual agreement
able to be transferred to another person's ownership legally
examples: The salary requirements are negotiable based on experience level
Contract terms remain negotiable until both parties sign
These negotiable securities can be sold on the open market
The check was negotiable and could be cashed by anyone

definitions: situated next to or very near another place
examples: The neighboring countries signed a peace treaty after years
Children from neighboring houses often played together after school

definitions: new or revived form of something from the past
examples: The neo classical architecture incorporated modern building techniques
Neo conservative policies gained support during the election campaign

definitions: relating to revival of classical styles in art and architecture
examples: The neoclassic building featured columns reminiscent of ancient Greece
Her neoclassic paintings combined traditional techniques with modern themes

definitions: relating to the revival of classical styles, especially in eighteenth-century art
examples: The neoclassical mansion displayed perfect symmetry in its design
Neoclassical economists believe markets naturally reach equilibrium without intervention

definitions: relating to modified liberalism favoring free-market capitalism and reduced government
examples: Neoliberal policies emphasized privatization of state-owned enterprises
Critics argued neoliberal economics increased inequality between rich and poor

definitions: relating to the later Stone Age when polished tools appeared
examples: Neolithic settlements showed evidence of early agricultural practices
The museum displayed neolithic pottery and farming implements

definitions: relating to newborn children, especially during their first month
examples: The hospital's neonatal unit cared for premature infants
Neonatal screening tests help detect genetic disorders early

definitions: settled or positioned comfortably within or against something
examples: The cottage nestled between rolling hills looked perfectly peaceful
The kitten nestled against its mother for warmth

definitions: lower in position, especially beneath the earth or below normal
examples: Ancient myths described journeys to the nether regions below
The spelunkers explored the nether depths of the cave system

definitions: remaining after all deductions have been made, especially financial
examples: The nett profit exceeded expectations after accounting for expenses
Her nett salary was lower after taxes and insurance

definitions: caught or covered with a net or net-like material
earned as profit after all deductions and expenses
examples: The netted fish struggled to escape from the trawler
The greenhouse plants were netted to protect from birds
The company netted millions despite the economic downturn
She netted a significant profit from the real estate sale

definitions: relating to nerves or the nervous system in organisms
examples: Neural pathways carry signals between the brain and body
Scientists studied neural activity during memory formation experiments

definitions: relating to neurology or the nervous system and its disorders
examples: The patient showed neurologic symptoms requiring immediate specialist attention
Neurologic examinations tested reflexes and nerve function

definitions: relating to the anatomy, functions, and disorders of nerves
examples: The neurological disorder affected her ability to control movement
Doctors ordered neurological tests to diagnose the mysterious symptoms

definitions: suffering from neurosis; unreasonably anxious, obsessive, or tense
examples: His neurotic behavior included checking the locks multiple times
The neurotic character in the play worried constantly about everything

definitions: of neither masculine nor feminine grammatical gender
lacking or having undeveloped sexual organs or characteristics
examples: German has neuter nouns requiring the article 'das'
The neuter pronoun 'it' refers to inanimate objects
The neuter worker bees cannot reproduce like the queen
Veterinarians often neuter pets to prevent unwanted breeding

definitions: rendered ineffective or harmless by opposing force or effect
examples: The acid was neutralised with a base solution safely
Their attack was neutralised by the strong defensive strategy

definitions: rendered ineffective or harmless by opposing force or effect
examples: The threat was neutralized before any damage could occur
Scientists neutralized the toxic waste using chemical treatments

definitions: recently born, especially referring to babies in first weeks
examples: The newborn baby slept peacefully in her mother's arms
Newborn screening tests check for genetic and metabolic disorders

definitions: recently discovered or established; newly found or acquired
examples: Her newfound confidence helped her excel at public speaking
They celebrated their newfound freedom after years of oppression

definitions: interesting or important enough to warrant reporting in news
examples: The scientific breakthrough was newsworthy enough for international coverage
Only newsworthy events make it to the evening broadcast

definitions: particularly good, skillful, or effective in a clever way
examples: That's a nifty gadget for opening stubborn jar lids
She showed us a nifty trick for folding fitted sheets

definitions: near in space, time, or relation; almost or nearly
examples: The end of winter is nigh as spring flowers bloom
It's nigh impossible to find parking downtown during festivals

definitions: happening or done every night or during the night
examples: The nightly news broadcast begins at six o'clock sharp
Their nightly ritual included reading bedtime stories together

definitions: resembling a nightmare; extremely frightening, unpleasant, or difficult
examples: The nightmarish traffic made the commute take three hours
Survivors described nightmarish conditions in the refugee camp

definitions: rejecting all religious and moral principles; believing life is meaningless
examples: His nihilistic philosophy rejected traditional values and beliefs completely
The nihilistic character saw no purpose in human existence

definitions: quick and light in movement or action; agile physically or mentally
examples: The nimble gymnast performed complex routines with apparent ease
Her nimble mind quickly grasped the mathematical concepts

definitions: equivalent to the sum of four and five; one more than eight
examples: The clock struck nine as they arrived at the theater
She works nine hours daily from morning until evening

definitions: equivalent to the sum of ten and nine; one more than eighteen
examples: At nineteen years old, she started her university studies
The nineteenth century brought major industrial and social changes

definitions: coming after the eighteenth in position, time, or order
examples: The nineteenth amendment gave American women the right to vote
They lived in a beautiful nineteenth century Victorian house

definitions: equivalent to the product of nine and ten; ten less than one hundred
examples: My grandmother celebrated her ninety years with a grand party
The temperature reached ninety degrees during the summer heatwave

definitions: coming after the eighth in position, time, or order
examples: She finished ninth in the marathon despite her injury
The ninth inning brought dramatic changes to the baseball game

definitions: of, containing, or relating to nitrogen in chemical compounds
examples: Nitric acid is commonly used in laboratory chemical reactions
The nitric oxide in the atmosphere affects air quality

definitions: of, containing, or relating to nitrogen, especially in lower valence
examples: Dentists use nitrous oxide as a mild anesthetic agent
The nitrous compounds in soil affect plant growth patterns

definitions: having or showing fine personal qualities or high moral principles
belonging to hereditary class with high social or political status
examples: His noble sacrifice saved many lives during the disaster
She pursued the noble goal of educating underprivileged children
The noble families gathered for the royal wedding ceremony
Ancient noble houses controlled vast estates and territories
